               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280110-225-person1335">
                  JOSEPH 
                  SOUTHEY
               <interp inst="t18280110-225-person1335" type="surname" value="SOUTHEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280110-225-person1335" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280110-225-person1335" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am shopman to Anthony Smith Johnson, of <placeName id="t18280110-225-crimeloc1185">Aldersgate-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280110-225-crimeloc1185" type="placeName" value="Aldersgate-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280110-225-crimeloc1185" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280110-225-off1183 t18280110-225-crimeloc1185"></join>. About six o'clock in the evening of the 26th of December, I was under the windowboard, and could not be seen; the prisoner came into the shop, looked round for about a minute, took a pair of boots, and walked away; I cried Stop thief! twice, and pursued him; he dropped them at the corner of Long-lane, crossed over, and turned round to walk towards Aldersgate-street again, and was taken - I never lost sight of him.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280110-225-person1336">
                  JOHN 
                  BUCE
               <interp inst="t18280110-225-person1336" type="surname" value="BUCE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280110-225-person1336" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280110-225-person1336" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a patrol. I heard the alarm, and took the prisoner.</p>
               <p>ANTHONY SMITH JOHNSON. I keep this shop, and was in the parlour at the time.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had just left my lodgings, and at the top of Long-lane I crossed the road; Southey came up, and said I had stolen the boots; a gentleman and lady gave me their address, and said they would prove I was not the man - they were here last night, and are gone into the country.</p>
               <p>ANTHONY SMITH JOHNSON. A lady and gentleman came into the shop, and left their card with the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280110-225-person1337">
                  JOSEPH 
                  SOUTHEY
               <interp inst="t18280110-225-person1337" type="surname" value="SOUTHEY"></interp>
